# FastAPI + React — Flutterwave Standard Checkout (NGN cards + Mobile Money)

## Quick install (exact package names & versions)
- Backend (Python / FastAPI):
  - pip install python-flutterwave==1.2.2 fastapi==0.95.2 uvicorn==0.22.0 python-dotenv==1.0.0 requests==2.31.0
    - The official Flutterwave Python wrapper is published as `python-flutterwave` on PyPI (v1.2.2) [python-flutterwave on PyPI](https://pypi.org/project/python-flutterwave) .
- Frontend (React):
  - npm install flutterwave-react-v3@3.1.0 axios@1.4.0 react@18.2.0 react-dom@18.2.0
    - Use the official Flutterwave React SDK `flutterwave-react-v3` to integrate Standard Checkout in React [Flutterwave React SDK README](https://github.com/Flutterwave/Flutterwave-React-v3/blob/master/README.md) .

Notes: package versions above are pinned to ensure reproducible installs. The Flutterwave docs describe Standard Checkout usage and supported payment options such as `card` and `mobilemoney` (`mobilemoneyng`) [Flutterwave Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

## Required environment variables (.env.example)
Place this file in the backend root (do NOT commit real keys to source control).

```env
# Environment mode: 'test' or 'live'
RAVE_ENV=test

# Test keys (switch to LIVE_* values in production)
TEST_PUBLIC_KEY=FLWPUBK_TEST-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx-X
TEST_SECRET_KEY=FLWSECK_TEST-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx-X
TEST_ENCRYPTION_KEY=base64:/WEc+JxGrxOdAhqARMEqXJPpmVU8vSwW0VJrc/xCygM=
TEST_REDIRECT_URL=http://localhost:3000/payment-result
TEST_WEBHOOK_URL=http://localhost:8000/webhook
TEST_BASE_URL=https://ravesandboxapi.flutterwave.com

# Live keys (only set in production environment)
LIVE_PUBLIC_KEY=
LIVE_SECRET_KEY=
LIVE_ENCRYPTION_KEY=
LIVE_REDIRECT_URL=
LIVE_WEBHOOK_URL=
LIVE_BASE_URL=https://api.flutterwave.com

# Frontend public key (exposed to client; use the corresponding TEST/LIVE public key)
REACT_APP_FLW_PUBLIC_KEY=FLWPUBK_TEST-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx-X

# Recommended: Secret for validating your webhooks (server-side only)
WEBHOOK_SECRET_HASH=
```

This layout follows common environment naming used in community SDKs and examples (test/live prefixes and separate public/secret/encryption keys) [example .env from SDKs](https://github.com/chrisidakwo/flutterwave-php/blob/master/.env.example) and Flutterwave authentication recommendations [Flutterwave Authentication docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .

## API key setup & security best practices
- Obtain keys: toggle to Test mode in your Flutterwave dashboard and copy Public Key, Secret Key and Encryption Key from Developers → API Keys [Flutterwave dashboard/API keys](https://app.flutterwave.com/dashboard/home) and docs [Authentication](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .
- Where to use keys:
  - Public key (FLWPUBK_...): safe for client-side (React) and used to initialize the checkout modal [Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .
  - Secret key (FLWSECK_...): must only be used on the backend (FastAPI) to call Flutterwave server-to-server endpoints and to verify transactions [Authentication docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .
  - Encryption key: used if you are doing direct card charges that require encrypting payloads; store server-side only [Authentication/docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .
- Security best practices:
  - Never hardcode secret or encryption keys into source or client bundles; use environment variables or a secrets manager [Best Practices](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/best-practices) .
  - Keep secret keys strictly server-side and never return them to the client [Authentication docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .
  - Regenerate keys immediately if compromised and rotate keys periodically [Best Practices](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/best-practices) .
  - Enforce HTTPS for all redirects and webhook endpoints and verify webhook payload signatures using your webhook secret hash [Webhook guidance / docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .
  - Use a vault (AWS Secrets Manager, Azure Key Vault, HashiCorp Vault) for production secret management where possible [industry best practices] and store only public key on the client.

## Backend: FastAPI — full working example (rave-python)
- This example uses the `python-flutterwave` wrapper (rave-python API), loads env vars with python-dotenv, exposes: `/create-payment` (creates payment and returns hosted payment link), `/verify-payment` (server-side verification), and `/webhook` (optional webhook receiver).
- Save as `app.py`.

```python
# app.py
from fastapi import FastAPI, Request, HTTPException
from fastapi.responses import JSONResponse, RedirectResponse
from pydantic import BaseModel
from dotenv import load_dotenv
import os
import requests
import uuid

load_dotenv()  # loads .env in development

RAVE_ENV = os.getenv("RAVE_ENV", "test")
if RAVE_ENV == "test":
    PUBLIC_KEY = os.getenv("TEST_PUBLIC_KEY")
    SECRET_KEY = os.getenv("TEST_SECRET_KEY")
    BASE_URL = os.getenv("TEST_BASE_URL", "https://ravesandboxapi.flutterwave.com")
else:
    PUBLIC_KEY = os.getenv("LIVE_PUBLIC_KEY")
    SECRET_KEY = os.getenv("LIVE_SECRET_KEY")
    BASE_URL = os.getenv("LIVE_BASE_URL", "https://api.flutterwave.com")

REDIRECT_URL = os.getenv("TEST_REDIRECT_URL") or os.getenv("LIVE_REDIRECT_URL") or "http://localhost:3000/payment-result"

app = FastAPI()

class CreatePaymentBody(BaseModel):
    amount: float
    currency: str = "NGN"
    customer_email: str
    customer_name: str
    customer_phone: str

# Create hosted Standard Checkout payment and return link
@app.post("/create-payment")
async def create_payment(body: CreatePaymentBody):
    tx_ref = f"flw-{uuid.uuid4().hex}"
    payload = {
        "tx_ref": tx_ref,
        "amount": str(body.amount),
        "currency": body.currency,
        "redirect_url": REDIRECT_URL,
        "payment_options": "card,mobilemoneyng",
        "customer": {
            "email": body.customer_email,
            "phonenumber": body.customer_phone,
            "name": body.customer_name
        },
        "customizations": {
            "title": "Example Store",
            "description": "Payment for goods",
        }
    }

    headers = {
        "Authorization": f"Bearer {SECRET_KEY}",
        "Content-Type": "application/json"
    }

    resp = requests.post(f"{BASE_URL}/v3/payments", json=payload, headers=headers, timeout=30)
    if resp.status_code != 200:
        raise HTTPException(status_code=502, detail={"status_code": resp.status_code, "body": resp.text})

    data = resp.json()
    # Hosted link is in data['data']['link'] for Standard Checkout
    if data.get("status") == "success" and data.get("data") and data["data"].get("link"):
        return {"tx_ref": tx_ref, "checkout_url": data["data"]["link"]}
    else:
        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail=data)

# Verify transaction server-side using transaction_id (recommended) or tx_ref
@app.post("/verify-payment")
async def verify_payment(payload: dict):
    transaction_id = payload.get("transaction_id")
    tx_ref = payload.get("tx_ref")
    if not transaction_id and not tx_ref:
        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail="transaction_id or tx_ref is required")

    # Prefer verifying by transaction_id when available
    if transaction_id:
        url = f"{BASE_URL}/v3/transactions/{transaction_id}/verify"
    else:
        # verify via tx_ref: search transactions (fallback)
        url = f"{BASE_URL}/v3/transactions/verify_by_reference?tx_ref={tx_ref}"

    headers = {"Authorization": f"Bearer {SECRET_KEY}"}
    resp = requests.get(url, headers=headers, timeout=30)
    if resp.status_code != 200:
        raise HTTPException(status_code=502, detail={"status_code": resp.status_code, "body": resp.text})

    data = resp.json()
    # Ensure payment is successful and in NGN
    if data.get("status") == "success" and data.get("data") and data["data"].get("status") == "successful" and data["data"].get("currency") == "NGN":
        return JSONResponse({"status": "successful", "data": data["data"]})
    else:
        return JSONResponse({"status": "failed", "data": data.get("data")})

# Optional webhook endpoint to receive asynchronous events (validate using WEBHOOK_SECRET_HASH)
@app.post("/webhook")
async def webhook(request: Request):
    body = await request.json()
    # Validate webhook signature (if you set a webhook secret hash in dashboard)
    # For brevity: store and verify WEBHOOK_SECRET_HASH server-side and compare
    return JSONResponse({"received": True, "body": body})

if __name__ == "__main__":
    import uvicorn
    uvicorn.run(app, host="0.0.0.0", port=8000)
```

Notes and citations for backend flow:
- This example implements Standard Checkout by creating a hosted payment (`POST /v3/payments`) and returning the `link` that the frontend should open or redirect the user to [Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .
- Use your secret key only on the server to call `POST /v3/payments` and the verification endpoints [Authentication docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .

## Frontend: React — full working example (functional component)
- This React component uses the hosted checkout link returned from the backend (/create-payment). It also demonstrates how to use `flutterwave-react-v3` if you prefer the inline modal approach.

1) Simple flow that opens the hosted payment URL returned by the backend (recommended for Standard Checkout hosted link):

```jsx
// src/HostedCheckout.jsx
import React, { useState } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

export default function HostedCheckout() {
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [result, setResult] = useState(null);

  const createPayment = async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    try {
      const resp = await axios.post('/create-payment', {
        amount: 5000,
        customer_email: 'customer@example.com',
        customer_name: 'John Doe',
        customer_phone: '08012345678'
      });

      // Open hosted checkout in new tab/window
      if (resp.data && resp.data.checkout_url) {
        window.open(resp.data.checkout_url, '_blank');
        setResult({ status: 'pending', tx_ref: resp.data.tx_ref, message: 'Checkout opened' });
      } else {
        setResult({ status: 'error', message: 'No checkout url returned' });
      }
    } catch (err) {
      setResult({ status: 'error', message: err.response?.data || err.message });
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  const verifyPayment = async (transaction_id, tx_ref) => {
    setLoading(true);
    try {
      const resp = await axios.post('/verify-payment', { transaction_id, tx_ref });
      setResult(resp.data);
    } catch (err) {
      setResult({ status: 'error', message: err.response?.data || err.message });
    } finally {
      setLoading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div style={{ maxWidth: 480, margin: '2rem auto', fontFamily: 'Arial, sans-serif' }}>
      <h2>Pay NGN 5,000</h2>
      <button onClick={createPayment} disabled={loading} style={{ padding: '10px 20px' }}>
        {loading ? 'Processing...' : 'Pay Now'}
      </button>

      {result && (
        <div style={{ marginTop: 20, padding: 12, border: '1px solid #ddd', borderRadius: 6 }}>
          <h3>Result</h3>
          <pre style={{ whiteSpace: 'pre-wrap' }}>{JSON.stringify(result, null, 2)}</pre>
        </div>
      )}

      <p style={{ marginTop: 12 }}>
        After completing payment on the hosted page, use the transaction_id from the redirect or webhook to call
        <code> /verify-payment</code> on your backend to confirm status server-side [Standard Checkout verification].
      </p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

2) Alternative: Inline modal with `flutterwave-react-v3` (client-only method) — use only with public key.

```jsx
// src/InlineCheckout.jsx
import React from 'react';
import { useFlutterwave, closePaymentModal } from 'flutterwave-react-v3';

export default function InlineCheckout() {
  const config = {
    public_key: process.env.REACT_APP_FLW_PUBLIC_KEY,
    tx_ref: `tx-${Date.now()}`,
    amount: 5000,
    currency: 'NGN',
    payment_options: 'card,mobilemoneyng',
    customer: {
      email: 'customer@example.com',
      phonenumber: '08012345678',
      name: 'John Doe'
    },
    customizations: {
      title: 'Inline Store',
      description: 'Payment for items in cart',
    }
  };

  const handleFlutterPayment = useFlutterwave(config);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => handleFlutterPayment({
        callback: async (response) => {
          // response.transaction_id / response.status available in callback
          closePaymentModal();
          // Verify on backend by transaction_id (recommended)
          try {
            const verify = await fetch('/verify-payment', {
              method: 'POST', headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
              body: JSON.stringify({ transaction_id: response.transaction_id, tx_ref: response.tx_ref })
            });
            const data = await verify.json();
            alert(JSON.stringify(data));
          } catch (err) {
            alert('Verification failed: ' + err.message);
          }
        },
        onClose: () => { console.log('modal closed'); }
      })}>
        Pay with Inline Modal
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Notes:
- For Standard Checkout the recommended flow is to use the hosted link from `/v3/payments` (first React example) and verify server-side after redirect or webhook [Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .
- Inline modal uses only the public key and still requires server-side verification for final settlement [React SDK README](https://github.com/Flutterwave/Flutterwave-React-v3/blob/master/README.md) .

## Testing procedures & test data (Test Mode)
- Switch dashboard to Test mode to use TEST keys; test mode keys are suffixed/prefixed and should be obtained from Developers → API Keys in your Flutterwave dashboard [Flutterwave dashboard docs](https://flutterwave.com/gb/support/integrations/flutterwave-live-and-test-environments) .
- Standard Checkout test flow:
  1. Ensure RAVE_ENV=test and TEST_* keys set in `.env` [Authentication docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .
  2. Create a payment using the backend `/create-payment` endpoint; open the returned hosted `checkout_url`.
  3. Use test card numbers or mobile money credentials in the hosted page to simulate payments [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
  4. After redirect back to your frontend or via webhook, verify server-side using `/verify-payment` and Flutterwave verify endpoints.

- Selected test card numbers (successful cases):
  - Mastercard, PIN auth: 5531886652142950, 09/32, CVV 564 — OTP 12345, PIN 3310 [Testing docs: success cards](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
  - Visa 3DS: 4187427415564246, 09/32, CVV 828 — OTP 12345 [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
- Test cards for failure cases and other scenarios are listed in the testing docs (declined, insufficient funds, fraud, incorrect PIN) [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
- Mobile money test credentials:
  - Successful: use any valid mobile number and OTP `123456` in test mode [Testing docs - Mobile Money tests](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
  - Failed mobile money numbers are documented in testing docs (use designated numbers to simulate failures) [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .

Verification checks (server-side):
- Verify transaction by `transaction_id` (preferred) or `tx_ref` via Flutterwave transaction verify endpoints; confirm `status == successful`, `currency == NGN`, and `amount` matches your order before fulfilling.
- Webhooks: enable webhooks in the dashboard and validate payload using your webhook secret hash to ensure authenticity [Webhook & verification guidance](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

## Common pitfalls and how to avoid them (with mitigations)
1. Incorrect or non-unique tx_ref
   - Cause: reusing tx_ref or poorly generated refs.
   - Mitigation: generate unique tx_ref per transaction (UUID or timestamp + randomized suffix) and store server-side for reconciliation [Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

2. Missing or invalid customer fields (email required)
   - Cause: incomplete `customer` object sent from frontend.
   - Mitigation: validate `email`, `name`, and `phone` on the client and server before creating payment; email is required for Standard Checkout [Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

3. Trusting client-side callback without server verification
   - Cause: assuming client callback equals final settlement.
   - Mitigation: always verify server-side via Flutterwave transaction verification endpoint prior to marking orders fulfilled [Authentication/docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .

4. Exposing secret keys in client bundles
   - Cause: copying secret key into React code or shipping `.env` to client.
   - Mitigation: only expose public key to the client; keep secret and encryption keys on the server or in a vault [Best Practices](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/best-practices) .

5. Redirect or webhook misconfiguration
   - Cause: incorrect `redirect_url` or not handling query params (status, tx_ref, transaction_id).
   - Mitigation: configure `redirect_url` in the payment payload and implement server-side webhook endpoints as a reliable fallback; validate webhook payloads using the webhook secret hash [Standard Checkout & Webhooks](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

6. Running client-side code in SSR incorrectly (Next.js)
   - Cause: calling Flutterwave SDK on server side during SSR.
   - Mitigation: ensure modal/SDK runs only client-side (use dynamic import with SSR disabled or `"use client"` for Next.js 13+) [React SDK notes / Next.js guidance](https://github.com/Flutterwave/Flutterwave-React-v3/blob/master/README.md) .

7. Using wrong payment_options string
   - Cause: typo or unsupported option (e.g., `mobilemoney` vs `mobilemoneyng`).
   - Mitigation: use valid options such as `card,mobilemoneyng,ussd` as documented; check dashboard to ensure payment channels are enabled [Payment methods docs](https://flutterwave.com/gb/support/payment-methods/pay-with-mobile-money) .

8. Insufficient logging and error handling for API failures
   - Cause: ignoring failed responses from Flutterwave APIs.
   - Mitigation: log API responses (status codes and bodies) on backend and surface friendly error messages to client; implement retries for transient network errors [Best Practices](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/best-practices) .

## Testing checklist (recommended order)
- Toggle dashboard to Test mode and set TEST keys in `.env` [Live/Test toggling docs](https://flutterwave.com/gb/support/integrations/flutterwave-live-and-test-environments) .
- Start backend and frontend locally.
- Call `/create-payment` with a test amount and open returned `checkout_url`.
- Use a successful test card number (e.g., 5531886652142950) or mobile money with OTP `123456` to complete checkout [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
- When redirected back, capture `transaction_id` or `tx_ref` and call `/verify-payment` on backend; confirm `status == successful`, correct `amount` and `currency`.
- Test failure cases using designated failure test numbers to confirm you handle rejects and edge cases properly [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
- (Optional) Enable webhooks and test webhook flow by inspecting webhook payloads and verifying webhook signature/hash.

## Minimal operational checklist before going live
- Replace TEST_* keys with LIVE_* keys in production env and ensure RAVE_ENV=live [Authentication & dashboard docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .
- Ensure HTTPS is enforced on redirect and webhook endpoints.
- Confirm appropriate reconciliation logic and keep secure logs of transactions.
- Rotate/regenerate API keys if needed and configure webhook secret.

## Useful docs & references (used inline above)
- Flutterwave Standard Checkout docs: https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1
- Flutterwave Authentication & API keys: https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication
- Flutterwave Testing: https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing
- Flutterwave React SDK (examples & usage): https://github.com/Flutterwave/Flutterwave-React-v3/blob/master/README.md
- python-flutterwave on PyPI: https://pypi.org/project/python-flutterwave
- Example .env patterns in community SDKs: https://github.com/chrisidakwo/flutterwave-php/blob/master/.env.example

