Verification checks (server-side):
- Verify transaction by `transaction_id` (preferred) or `tx_ref` via Flutterwave transaction verify endpoints; confirm `status == successful`, `currency == NGN`, and `amount` matches your order before fulfilling.
- Webhooks: enable webhooks in the dashboard and validate payload using your webhook secret hash to ensure authenticity [Webhook & verification guidance](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

## Common pitfalls and how to avoid them (with mitigations)
1. Incorrect or non-unique tx_ref
   - Cause: reusing tx_ref or poorly generated refs.
   - Mitigation: generate unique tx_ref per transaction (UUID or timestamp + randomized suffix) and store server-side for reconciliation [Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

2. Missing or invalid customer fields (email required)
   - Cause: incomplete `customer` object sent from frontend.
   - Mitigation: validate `email`, `name`, and `phone` on the client and server before creating payment; email is required for Standard Checkout [Standard Checkout docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

3. Trusting client-side callback without server verification
   - Cause: assuming client callback equals final settlement.
   - Mitigation: always verify server-side via Flutterwave transaction verification endpoint prior to marking orders fulfilled [Authentication/docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .

4. Exposing secret keys in client bundles
   - Cause: copying secret key into React code or shipping `.env` to client.
   - Mitigation: only expose public key to the client; keep secret and encryption keys on the server or in a vault [Best Practices](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/best-practices) .

5. Redirect or webhook misconfiguration
   - Cause: incorrect `redirect_url` or not handling query params (status, tx_ref, transaction_id).
   - Mitigation: configure `redirect_url` in the payment payload and implement server-side webhook endpoints as a reliable fallback; validate webhook payloads using the webhook secret hash [Standard Checkout & Webhooks](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/flutterwave-standard-1) .

6. Running client-side code in SSR incorrectly (Next.js)
   - Cause: calling Flutterwave SDK on server side during SSR.
   - Mitigation: ensure modal/SDK runs only client-side (use dynamic import with SSR disabled or `"use client"` for Next.js 13+) [React SDK notes / Next.js guidance](https://github.com/Flutterwave/Flutterwave-React-v3/blob/master/README.md) .

7. Using wrong payment_options string
   - Cause: typo or unsupported option (e.g., `mobilemoney` vs `mobilemoneyng`).
   - Mitigation: use valid options such as `card,mobilemoneyng,ussd` as documented; check dashboard to ensure payment channels are enabled [Payment methods docs](https://flutterwave.com/gb/support/payment-methods/pay-with-mobile-money) .

8. Insufficient logging and error handling for API failures
   - Cause: ignoring failed responses from Flutterwave APIs.
   - Mitigation: log API responses (status codes and bodies) on backend and surface friendly error messages to client; implement retries for transient network errors [Best Practices](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/best-practices) .

## Testing checklist (recommended order)
- Toggle dashboard to Test mode and set TEST keys in `.env` [Live/Test toggling docs](https://flutterwave.com/gb/support/integrations/flutterwave-live-and-test-environments) .
- Start backend and frontend locally.
- Call `/create-payment` with a test amount and open returned `checkout_url`.
- Use a successful test card number (e.g., 5531886652142950) or mobile money with OTP `123456` to complete checkout [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
- When redirected back, capture `transaction_id` or `tx_ref` and call `/verify-payment` on backend; confirm `status == successful`, correct `amount` and `currency`.
- Test failure cases using designated failure test numbers to confirm you handle rejects and edge cases properly [Testing docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/testing) .
- (Optional) Enable webhooks and test webhook flow by inspecting webhook payloads and verifying webhook signature/hash.

## Minimal operational checklist before going live
- Replace TEST_* keys with LIVE_* keys in production env and ensure RAVE_ENV=live [Authentication & dashboard docs](https://developer.flutterwave.com/v3.0/docs/authentication) .
- Ensure HTTPS is enforced on redirect and webhook endpoints.
- Confirm appropriate reconciliation logic and keep secure logs of transactions.
- Rotate/regenerate API keys if needed and configure webhook secret.

